Part A¶

Question 1:¶

Measures The Strength of Relationships between People in A Mapped Network of People.¶

To answer this question, we would like to utilize a package to analyse the connection from Collin, Boris and Rachel networks.

Methods¶

  • networkx package
  • https://networkx.github.io/documentation/stable/

Features¶

Some Features would apply into this network analysis model:

  • phone or email, combining into a feature.
  • network owner: Collin, Rachel and Boris
  • networks' connections

Findings¶

  • Collin has most strong connections in the network.
  • 18 people with 3rd degree have high strength connections with Collin, Boris and Rachel.

class MultiColumnLabelEncoder:
    def __init__(self,columns = None):
        self.columns = columns

    def fit(self,X,y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self,X):
        '''
        transform columns of X specified in self.columns using
        LabelEncoder(). If no columns specified, transform all
        columns in X.
        '''
        output = X.copy()
        if self.columns is not None:
            for col in self.columns:
                output[col] = LabelEncoder().fit_transform(output[col])
        else:
            for colname,col in output.iteritems():
                output[colname] = LabelEncoder().fit_transform(col)
        return output

    def fit_transform(self,X,y=None):
        return self.fit(X,y).transform(X)

Part B¶

Question 4:¶

We need to figure out how to identify a person’s occupation, title or role given an incomplete set of information.¶

In this case, there are around 2,000 people with limited information but need to predict almost 200 different job titles. This is a multiple classification question with various outputs(y).

Methods¶

In order to solve this case, some methods I will develop as following steps:

  1. create a feature called job_segment to segment job titles in different groups. We will be based on job_segment to create different classification models for predicting outputs(y). For example:

    • Engineering: Chemical Engineer and Software Test Engineer III etc.
    • Finance: Tax Accountant and Financial Advisor etc.
    • Business_Development: Sales and Business Development Manager etc.

  2. Features and Observations in this data set are insufficient so we will need to collect extra data from social media websites:

    • LinkedIn API

      • https://developer.linkedin.com/docs/v1/people/profile-api
      • https://developer.linkedin.com/docs/rest-api
      • https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/linkedin/shared/integrations/people/profile-api

    • Facebook API

      • https://developers.facebook.com/docs/graph-api/reference/user/
      • https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-use-facebook-graph-api-and-extract-data-using-python-1839e19d6999

Features and Outputs¶

Engineering for Inputs¶

There are extra features would collect from LinkedIn API and Facebook API:

  • Education and Major
  • Personal Headline(usually show job title at xxx company)
  • Industry
  • Others
    • ex. country, location and work history

These features are very crucial information to implementing into segment-based training models.

Engineering for outputs¶

In regards to the output, need to build up a dictionary to attribute similar job titles into some categories, which would reduces output classes increases the prediction performance potentially. For example:

job_title_adjust = {
                    'Business Development Manager':['Sales Manger','Business Manager'],
                    'Soft Engineer':['Developer','back-end Engineer','Soft Engineer']
                    }

Therefore, we can reduce a segment-based model with less predicting output classes, which give us a better predicting outputs of scale.

Challenges & Suggestions¶

To acquire extra information, integration and automation works with APIs might take some resources and times to develop but it is an important step before creating a well prediction model.
